01:18.159 --> 01:23.280
can prepare a family of quantum states approximating the ground state.

13
01:23.280 --> 01:32.000
Next, we need an estimator, a means of estimating the expectation value of the operator H over the current variational

14
01:32.000 --> 01:38.159
quantum state. Sometimes what we really care about is simply this expectation value, which we

15
01:38.159 --> 01:44.960
call a cost function. Other times we care about a more complicated function that can still be written starting from

16
01:44.960 --> 01:48.079
one or more expectation values.

17
01:48.079 --> 01:56.000
Finally, we need a classical optimizer, an algorithm that varies parameters to try to minimize this cost function.

18
01:56.000 --> 02:02.240
Let's outline the problem we want to solve and the general approach before addressing how quantum plays a role. We

19
02:02.240 --> 02:10.239
can cast many optimization problems critical to science and industry as matrix value problems. Commonly, you

20
02:10.239 --> 02:17.599
want the minimum igen value of your matrix and the igen vector that corresponds to it. The matrix H could be

